Biodiversity in National Parks¶

The investigation was conducted based on data provided by CodeCademy

In this researchwe will look at:

  • distribution of species by category
  • distribution of conservation_status by park_name
  • distribution of conservation_status by category
  • Amount of animals and plants in parks
  • distribution of observations by specie
  • the most and the least observed species in the parks

First import all necessary libraries

Column meanimg:


    

  • scientific_name - the scientific name of each species
    • 

  • park_name - name of the park where observations took place
    • 

  • observations - how many times 'scientific_name' spicie was spoted in particular park
    • 












Seems to be a good dataset: without missing data and appropriate data types. There are some duplicates that we need to take care of.











Each park's name ends with "National Park" which adds very little information but makes the table cumbersome. Let's eliminate these words

There are 5541 distinct scientific_names while there are 5824 lines in the data frame. It min there are duplicates in the scientific_name category which makes no sense because one species cannot have 2 or more different conservation_status or simultaneously belong to different 'categories'. The only reason the previous report didn't show us any duplicates is different common_name that can easily happen.











Columns meaning:


    

  • category - class of animal
    • 

  • scientific_name - the scientific name of each species
    • 

  • common_name - the common names of each species
    • 

  • conservation_status - each species’ current conservation status
    • 












I suggest that NAN in conservation_status means that particular species didn't require any concern therefore replace NAN with No Concern.











In [6]:



     


species.conservation_status.fillna('No Concern', inplace = True)



     















Delete duplicates¶










In [7]:



     


# delete duplicates in observations 
obs = observations.loc[:,['scientific_name', 'park_name']]
obs.drop_duplicates(inplace = True)
obs1 = observations.loc[:,['observations']]
observations = obs.join(obs1).reset_index(drop = True)
print('length of observations file after duplicates removed', len(observations))


# delete duplicates in species 
spec = species.scientific_name
spec.drop_duplicates(inplace = True)
spec1 = species.loc[:, species.columns != 'scientific_name']
pd.merge(spec1, spec, left_index=True, right_index=True)
print('length of species file after duplicates removed', len(species))



     


















    
    






length of observations file after duplicates removed 22164
length of species file after duplicates removed 5824

First, let's look at live beings distribution for all data we have including with no concern¶










In [12]:



     


plt.figure(figsize = ( 12, 6))
order = ['Vascular Plant', 'Bird', 'Nonvascular Plant', 'Mammal', 'Fish', 'Reptile', 'Amphibian']
sns.countplot(data = df, x = 'category', order= order)
plt.title('Number of species  in each category')



     


















    
    
Out[12]:








Text(0.5, 1.0, 'Number of species  in each category')










    
    



























The vascular plant takes an overwhelming majority of species presented in the parks. Amphibians are the least group of species. Here we have a power-law distribution, which makes sense - plants are at the bottom of the feeding chain.











let's see how many different species belong to one or another conservation status in each park¶










In [13]:



     


plt.figure(figsize = (18,6))
plt.subplot(121)
sns.countplot(data = species_that_need_care, x = 'park_name',  hue = 'conservation_status')
plt.title('Number of species  that belongs to one or another conservation_status category')

df2 = species_that_need_care.groupby('conservation_status', ).count()
text1 = 'conservation_status'
for i in df2.index:
    text1 += '\n\n' + str(i)
    
text2 = 'number of species '
for i in df2.category:
    text2 += '\n\n' + str(i)  
    
plt.subplot(122)
plt.axis('off')
plt.text(0.0, 0.6, text1)
plt.text(0.4, 0.6, text2)



     


















    
    
Out[13]:








Text(0.4, 0.6, 'number of species \n\n64\n\n16\n\n644\n\n40')










    
    



























We can see that all parks show the same result (notice graph shove number of species not a number of animals/observations in a category): most of the species belong to 'Species of concern ' category, 'in recovery' is the smallest category. Fact that all parks have the same bar plot means that all species are present in each park.











Distribution of conservation_status by category¶










In [14]:



     


plt.figure(figsize = (18,18))
plt.subplot(421)
sns.countplot(data = species_that_need_care, x = 'category',  hue = 'conservation_status', order= order)
plt.legend(loc = 1)
plt.title('Distribution of conservation_status by category, number of species')

category = species_that_need_care.category.unique().tolist()
for i in range(len(category)):
    plt.subplot(420 + i + 2)
    sns.countplot(data = species_that_need_care[species_that_need_care['category'] == category[i]], x = 'category',  hue = 'conservation_status')
    plt.legend(loc = 1)
    plt.title('Distribution of conservation_status for {}'.format(category[i]))
plt.tight_layout()



     


















    
    



























Pay attention that on the graph above each plot have a different meaning for different colors. The birds category has the most species that need care. At the same time birds the only category that has 'in recovery' conservation status. The least suffering categories (approximately the same number of species that need care) are reptile, nonvascular plant, and amphibian.

Observation vs species¶










In [16]:



     


plt.figure(figsize = (18,20))
conservation_status = df.conservation_status.unique().tolist()

for i in range(len(conservation_status)):

    plt.subplot(5,2,1 + 2*i)
    sns.barplot(data = df, x = df.category[df.conservation_status == conservation_status[i]], y = 'observations', estimator = sum, order= order )
    plt.title('Observations of {} animals and plants'.format(conservation_status[i]))

    plt.subplot(5,2,(2 + 2*i))
    sns.countplot(data = species, x = species.category[species.conservation_status == conservation_status[i]], order= order)
    plt.title(conservation_status[i] + ' species')
plt.tight_layout()



     


















    
    



























The more dangerous the conservation status the fewer species are there. Mammals are the most endangered category. The least endangered are amphibians and vascular plants.


It worth mention about In the Recovery category only 3 species of birds and 1 species of mammals in recovery. All other categories have no recovery species.











The most and the least observed species in the parks¶










In [17]:



     


t = pd.DataFrame()
for park in df['park_name'].unique():
    park_df = df[df.park_name == park]  
    max_observations = park_df.observations.max()
    t = pd.concat([t, park_df[park_df.observations == max_observations]])
print('\n', pd.DataFrame(t).reset_index(drop = True,).to_string())

t = pd.DataFrame()
for park in df['park_name'].unique():
    park_df = df[df.park_name == park]  
    max_observations = park_df.observations.min()
    t = pd.concat([t, park_df[park_df.observations == max_observations]])
print('\n', pd.DataFrame(t).reset_index(drop = True,).to_string())

Conclusions¶










    

  • Amount of species in the category have a power-law distribution, which makes sense - plants are at the bottom of the feeding chain.
    • 

  • All species are present in each park.
    • 

  • Birds category has the most species that need care. At the same time birds the only category that has 'in recovery' conservation status. The least suffering categories (approximately the same number of species that need care) are reptile, nonvascular plant, and amphibian.
    • 

  • Distribution of animals and plants observed positively correlates with park size
    • 

  • Mammals are the most endangered category, the least endangered are amphibians and vascular plants.
    •
